Yes, race is widely recognized as a social construct rather than a biological reality. This perspective is supported by extensive research in anthropology, sociology, and genetics, which demonstrates that the concept of race is shaped by social, economic, and political forces rather than distinct biological differences.

Historically, race has been used to categorize and stratify people based on perceived differences, often to justify discrimination and inequality. These categorizations are arbitrary and have evolved over time and across societies. For instance, the racial categories we use today were created by humans and unfolded as they did because of our history. ([otherwords.org](https://otherwords.org/race-is-a-social-construct-but-it-still-matters/?utm_source=openai))

Scientific studies have shown that genetic differences among human populations are subtle and do not align with traditional racial categories. The full genomes of individuals from different racial backgrounds reveal more genetic variation within so-called racial groups than between them. For example, the genomes of two individuals of European ancestry can be more different from each other than from an individual of Asian ancestry. ([livescience.com](https://www.livescience.com/53613-race-is-social-construct-not-scientific.html?utm_source=openai))

The concept of race has been used to rationalize social inequalities as "natural." However, race resides not in nature but in politics, economics, and culture. Our social institutions "make" race by disproportionately channeling resources, power, status, and wealth to certain groups. ([en.wikipedia.org](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Race%3A_The_Power_of_an_Illusion?utm_source=openai))

In summary, race is a social construct without a biological basis. It is a product of historical and cultural factors, used to categorize and stratify people based on perceived differences. Recognizing race as a social construct is crucial for understanding and addressing the social inequalities and discrimination that arise from these arbitrary classifications. 

